threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: PE32+ executable (native) x86-64, for MS Windows

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This is a 64-bit Windows kernel rootkit designed to hide network activity. It hooks the TCP/IP driver by replacing the IRP_MJ_DEVICE_CONTROL dispatch routine for `\Device\Tcp`. The hook function (`sub_12b04`) and an IRP completion routine (`sub_12410`) intercept and manipulate network-related data structures, likely to hide malicious connections from monitoring tools. The driver also interacts with `\Device\IPFILTERDRIVER`, suggesting firewall rule manipulation. The use of MDLs to map and modify kernel memory further indicates its rootkit capabilities.
